Yes, Abraham Lincoln played a significant role in the abolition of slavery in the United States. As the 16th President of the United States, Lincoln was a prominent advocate for the abolition of slavery and he took several important steps toward this goal. In 1862, Lincoln signed the Emancipation Proclamation, which declared that all slaves in the Confederate states "shall be then, thenceforward, and forever free." While this did not immediately free all slaves in the United States, it was a major step towards ending the institution of slavery and it signaled the federal government's commitment to the cause of abolition. The 13th Amendment to the United States Constitution, which was ratified in 1865, officially abolished slavery and involuntary servitude in the United States. Lincoln played a key role in advocating for the passage of this amendment, which was one of the major achievements of his presidency. Overall, Lincoln played a critical role in the abolition of slavery and is widely recognized as a champion of the cause of freedom and human rights.